About a year or so ago I tried downloading some Switch modding software and tried hacking Animal Crossing New Horizons. My goal was to make a mod that added a dating feature into the game, or at least something close to it. I didn't have much prior experience in video game modding but I figured it couldn't be that hard since I was primarily just editing text.
Holy shit I was wrong. Apparently all of the text files in Animal Crossing games are in one of Nintendo's proprietary formats, and finding an editor that can handle them is a pain in the ass. I'd love to make a real HMOFA mod but I guess I'll have to find someone to shepherd me through that stuff. Maybe I'll give it another try here soon. As far as I know Animal Crossing has never had any fan games or ROM hacks but I think one could be a lot of fun.

>why the hell is that sauce radioactive green?
Made from green habanero peppers, just before they ripen into blaze orange. Tends to be slightly less hot than ripe habaneros, and a bit if a bitter edge. I wouldn't touch that dish, it's pretty disgusting. But, I do eat that exact same green habanero sauce on a lot of other stuff. I also make my own when I live in a place where I can tend a small garden. Although, the last time I did that it was with scorpion peppers, bumped up a bit with some Carolina Reapers. At the end of the growing season after I harvested all the best ripe peppers, I collect all th egreen & partially ripe peppers from everything (a combination of habanero, ghost, scorpion, and Carolina Reapers) and chop everything into a pot with some garlic, avocado oil and a dash or two of balsamic vinegar, simmer it down until a good bit of the water evaporates, than seal it in a jar while it's still boiling hot. Shit'll keep for a couple years in the back of the refrigerator, waiting for you to open it. That after-harvest slaw will clean your pipes out something fierce and thorough. Not quite that radioactive green, but still pretty green and it'll fool the Hell out of you until it's far too late.

Pure opinion and speculation here but I think ai crossing over with a now known to be slow paced and slow to update story might be a factor on ai advancing forward in time. If ai advances in universe time to any significant degree it could require either waiting for the crossover story to move as well, spoiling details about crossover characters, or not using the crossover characters as much. That all depends on mutual planning and how deep the crossover runs. Meshing finicky creative workflows together even lightly can introduce weird and unexpected problems that the parties involved don't want to admit to. This is why cameos are generally done, or crossovers after one story is done.
However, how much of a factor it really is for ai only the writer knows. My speculation could be wildly off and it's 99% pandemic malaise related instead. In which case this is food for thought for other writers.
